Visited in February for a weekday dinner. Good, solid neighborhood sushi spot, with reasonable prices and a nice range of fishes to choose from. Would definitely return next time I'm in the area. The style is largely traditional with a little bit of creative twist. Favorite piece of the night was NZ king salmon topped with torched tamato. The refreshing sourness of the tomato went superbly with the richness of the salmon belly. The sesame tofu pudding as dessert was also excellent. Other good pieces included shima aji, hotate, and unagi. Personally I found that the more creative pieces, such as otoro+uni+caviar and akami+torched mushrooms+truffles were a little too much for me, but that's just my taste. The chef uses less rice in the sushi compared with other places, but this does not mess up the balance and I still ended up very full from my meal.

It was pretty good. Pieces are smaller than other spots and they use so little rice. They have some work to do I’m terms of finding their sushi to rice ratio balance and they will get me as a repeat customer 😁🍣 oh yea dessert was excellent. Make reservations!

Had the full omakase, which was really delicious, unique, beautifully designed and quite filling. Fish were fresh, the dishes were all very special and original and service was perfect. The one comment I have is about the ambiance. The restaurant was a little too bright and plainly decorated, which took away from the experience.
You would be surprised by the quality of the fish here. On par if not better than some other omakase found in the city
Fantastic and unique omakase at a great price point. Definitely sit and eat at the sushi bar.

I had chicken katsudon with miso soup and was really impressed with the presentation of the food and how fresh it was. Of course it was yummy! Was pleasantly surprised it included daikon root, sauteed onions, and raw broccoli and brussel sprouts (everything tasted good in the dipping sauce). In a lot of ways this is a very traditional Japanese restaurant from the hot hand towels at the beginning of the meal to how we were not rushed out at the end. Even the bathroom was nice. We'll be returning!

I booked a last minute table for my friend's birthday because we love omakase and many places require booking a month in advanced, but Sushi Lin seems relatively lesser known for now. I heard about this place from the nycomakase Instagram page. We've been to Tanoshi and Nakazawa so far but what we loved about Sushi Lin was that although we might say the portions are slightly smaller (thumb length vs index finger length), the flavors are very innovative and unique, particularly the use of their house made soy sauce and truffle. We ordered the sushi/sashimi omakase for $80, which gave us four sashimi dishes (with at least two pieces each) and 8 sushi pieces, ending with one handroll - which was a little too oily for my taste, but for the most part they were all so delicious it was hard to choose a favourite to order extra pieces of. We also ordered the oyster sampler, which could have used a little less sauce, as it was overpowering, but the textures of the oysters were delicious. We would definitely come here again and try the chef's omakase at the counter.

The very wide price range at which sushi can be bought makes sushi restaurants particularly hard to review and compare. Generally speaking of course, you get what you pay for but that being said the very high end of sushi dining that can top at $600 per person is out of reach for most people. For me then the trick becomes to find the rare pearl in the vast middle ground between grocery store sushi and super expensive Omakases.  Sushi Lin is such a place and I'd challenge anyone to find better value than their $26 sushi dinner comprising of nine pieces of sushi and one Maki roll. The sushi is simply delicious, fresh and prepared with obvious skill and care. It will therefore not surprise anyone to read that the two chefs and co-owners are veterans of high end sushi places. Although this might make a future reservation more difficult, I couldn't recommend it any more, it's a true gem.  PS Omakase options priced at $60, $80 and $100 are also on offer.

Sushi Lin is a hidden gem of NYC. Although it is located in Brooklyn, Sushi Lin is relatively close to the city and the quality of the food definitely makes the drive worth it.  After finding out about this place, I go about twice a week and always opt for the omikase and a roll. There are 4 omikase choices, each giving you an overview of the menu. Furthermore, the staff and chefs are extremely friendly and go above and beyond to make the customer happy.  They bring you a warm towel when you first sit down and are quick to refill your water/tea. Honestly, I have nothing but good things to say about Sushi Lin, and I am on vacation right now, dreaming to get back to the city to get some more sushi. 10/10 would recommend!

The perfect balance of salt, rice and charred fatty fish melts into your mouth into a tsunami of flavor.  I'm gonna work hard in my job and make more money so I can afford to come here more often! Its that darn good!

Absolutely phenomenal! A dedicated Geido fan for many years, I was amused to find a new Chinese-owned sushi place opening next door - so I took a look. The quality of food and service at Sushi Lin blew my expectations away. Instead of focusing on different kinds of sushi rolls like Geido, Sushi Lin is a mellower joint for the serious fish lovers. I ordered the Sashimi Dinner and the Chawamushi. The former was incredibly fresh (see photos) and the latter was delicate and delightful.  My server was attentive and professional. I would most certainly come back to Sushi Lin for its high-quality sashimi and tranquil ambience. Highly recommend!
